``<number>..<number>``
. Currently, you can use it with the new 
``range``
 command, which lets you do commands like:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
ls | range 3..5

```
And return rows 3 through 5 of the table that 
``ls``
 gives you.
íźźŕqTitle: title: Nushell 0.7.0
Path: Ranges (wycats, sebastian-xyz)
Content:
We've added ranges as new fundamental type in Nu. To use it, use 
``<number>..<number>``
. Currently, you can use it with the new 
``range``
 command, which lets you do commands like:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
ls | range 3..5

```
And return rows 3 through 5 of the table that 
``ls``
 gives you.
óŔWarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/blog/2019-12-18-nushell-0_7_0.mdŔ@4d2cff5c97bdb7aeacbca6fa5239a6f19b3ab5e7c166bc3a8d8d576bce051e85ītitle: Nushell 0.7.0ĎŔ$Autocomplete improvements (sophiajt)ŕsAs we improve the parser, we are getting more opportunities to do more with the results. One feature we added recently is the ability to autocomplete flags for internal commands.
For example, if you want to see what's available for the 
``config``
 command, you can now type 
``config --``
 and then immediately use the 
``<tab>``
 key to cycle through possible options.
íźźŕ√Title: title: Nushell 0.7.0
Path: Autocomplete improvements (sophiajt)
Content:
As we improve the parser, we are getting more opportunities to do more with the results. One feature we added recently is the ability to autocomplete flags for internal commands.
For example, if you want to see what's available for the 
``config``
 command, you can now type 
``config --``
 and then immediately use the 
``<tab>``
 key to cycle through possible options.
óŔWarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/blog/2019-12-18-nushell-0_7_0.mdŔ@1fd9ae4b171e10f2e3b12cc34aeca1a900ace30b9026fe1b9e7226400300e377ītitle: Nushell 0.7.0ĎŔ-Nu becomes multiple crates (wycats, sophiajt)ŕŽPart of a big effort to get Nu ready for script support is to refactor the current codebase to make it cleaner and easier to work with.
For the last few weeks, a big part of this refactor involved splitting our growing monolith of a codebase into separate sub-crates that work together to give the same functionality. As we've done so, we've been able to clean up some of the interfaces between the code. The end result is something that already is easier to work with, and we're excited about what this means for future development.
One side effect of this work is that we've now separated out the plugins from the main 
``nu``
 crate. This gives you more options to configure your Nu setup how you want, as each optional crate can be separately installed.
From cargo, you can install the main crate with:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
cargo install nu

```
Then, you can install the plugins the same way. You can find them because they have a name starting with 
``nu_plugin_``
. For example, to install the textview plugin:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
cargo install nu_plugin_textview

```
The current set of plugins includes:
nu_plugin_average
nu_plugin_binaryview
nu_plugin_fetch
nu_plugin_inc
nu_plugin_match
nu_plugin_post
nu_plugin_ps
nu_plugin_str
nu_plugin_sum
nu_plugin_sys
nu_plugin_textview
nu_plugin_tree
By default, Nu will install a small set of these plugins ("sys", "ps", "textview", "inc", "str"). You can optionally turn this off using:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
cargo install nu --no-default-features

```
íźźŕDTitle: title: Nushell 0.7.0
Path: Nu becomes multiple crates (wycats, sophiajt)
Content:
Part of a big effort to get Nu ready for script support is to refactor the current codebase to make it cleaner and easier to work with.
For the last few weeks, a big part of this refactor involved splitting our growing monolith of a codebase into separate sub-crates that work together to give the same functionality. As we've done so, we've been able to clean up some of the interfaces between the code. The end result is something that already is easier to work with, and we're excited about what this means for future development.
One side effect of this work is that we've now separated out the plugins from the main 
``nu``
 crate. This gives you more options to configure your Nu setup how you want, as each optional crate can be separately installed.
From cargo, you can install the main crate with:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
cargo install nu

```
Then, you can install the plugins the same way. You can find them because they have a name starting with 
``nu_plugin_``
. For example, to install the textview plugin:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
cargo install nu_plugin_textview

```
The current set of plugins includes:
nu_plugin_average
nu_plugin_binaryview
nu_plugin_fetch
nu_plugin_inc
nu_plugin_match
nu_plugin_post
nu_plugin_ps
nu_plugin_str
nu_plugin_sum
nu_plugin_sys
nu_plugin_textview
nu_plugin_tree
By default, Nu will install a small set of these plugins ("sys", "ps", "textview", "inc", "str"). You can optionally turn this off using:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
cargo install nu --no-default-features

```
óŔWarchive/external_nushell_repo_backup/nushell.github.io/blog/2019-12-18-nushell-0_7_0.mdŔ@fb80952a2ee7bd20c36fd87081994e172f4af49e21ff9849fbcc0d576aece04bītitle: Nushell 0.7.0ĎŔ)Introducing: stable and unstable featuresŕVAnother part of the current refactor work is that we're splitting the "stable" and "unstable" features up. This lets us experiment a bit easier before a command becomes a stable part of the releases.
Now, to install all the stable features, you can use:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
cargo install nu --features=stable

```
If you want to get both stable 
and
 unstable features, use:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
cargo install nu --all-features

```
Warning: unless you're working on Nu itself you may not want to install all features currently, as you'll see that we're working on an internal tracing tool.
íźźŕęTitle: title: Nushell 0.7.0
Path: Introducing: stable and unstable features
Content:
Another part of the current refactor work is that we're splitting the "stable" and "unstable" features up. This lets us experiment a bit easier before a command becomes a stable part of the releases.
Now, to install all the stable features, you can use:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
cargo install nu --features=stable

```
If you want to get both stable 
and
 unstable features, use:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
cargo install nu --all-features

```
Warning: unless you're working on Nu itself you may not want to install all features currently, as you'll see that we're working on an internal tracing tool.
